        "type": "text",
        "name": "Text",
        "title": "What are common mistakes to avoid when starting a digital transformation? ",
        "headerType": "like-h2",
        "titleAlignment": null,
        "style": "light",
        "decorator": "none",
        "content": "<ul>\n\t<li>Digital transformation is not a one-time&nbsp;activity --&nbsp;it is a continuous, ongoing&nbsp;process that cannot be planned&nbsp;and scheduled.</li>\n\t<li>Adding Amazon or Alibaba sales channels might be a step forward, but it that alone does not complete a digital transformation strategy.</li>\n\t<li>Building in-house solutions are time-consuming and expensive&nbsp;and may not guarantee results.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Successful digital transformation is a continuous agile process, where&nbsp;companies innovate in measured steps, gaining regular market feedback to move forward incrementally. Digital transformation requires change management and a readiness to adopt according to market demands. Lost opportunities occur when companies spend a year planning and preparing for a project that lasts the next two years. Companies should launch, learn, and re-launch in an ongoing cycle reacting to changing conditions and customer needs.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Making short-term-fixes,&nbsp;such as adding a simple shopping cart to an existing&nbsp;website, using Amazon as a sales channel, or delivering basic online order management options to customers,&nbsp;may seem like a good place to start; however, there is much more to consider when it comes to digital transformation. The primary goal of digital transformation is to truly know the customer by gaining control of the customer experience and building intimacy to drive engagement.</p>\n\n<p>According to experts, 80% of an ecommerce platform development budget&nbsp;is spent on general platform functionality and only 20% is allocated for high value, market-specific&nbsp;features. Therefore, it can be cost prohibitive to develop home-grown functionality in-house, making the digital transformation&nbsp;more expensive, resource-intensive, and&nbsp;laborious ongoing effort.</p>\n",
